Question 2- Think your refrigerator is just one big box of evenly cold air?

104
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:07,000
Not so. The temperature inside the average fridge actually varies from front to back, bottom to top and everywhere in between.

105
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:15,000
Because of this, food product placement within the appliance is far more important than you probably realise.

106
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:26,000
The whole purpose of the modern refrigerator is to slow the growth of bacteria which thrive in temperatures from 4.4 to 60 degrees Celsius.

107
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:35,000
As a result, refrigerators are typically set at or below that low end to protect foods against bacteria.

108
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:48,000
Although it might seem like time spent organising the fridge will spoil your day, doing so will actually make it more user friendly, easier to clean and food safety conscious.

109
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:59,000
Those little bins on the inside of refrigerator doors are convenient, but they don't maintain a consistent temperature, so definitely refrain from putting perishable foods in there.

110
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:08,000
The top area is not as cold as the bottom of the fridge, so save it for the foods that don't need extra chilly temperatures.

111
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:13,000
Store foods that are ready to eat or already cooked on the top shelf.

112
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:19,000
The middle shelf is the most temperature controlled part of the fridge, so place eggs here.

113
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:26,000
Drinks and prepared foods can also live on the middle shelf if you run out of room up top.

114
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:36,000
The back of the bottom shelf is the coldest spot in the fridge, so store perishable dairy products here to keep them edible longer.

115
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:44,000
Never store foods with high water content here because the water within them can and will freeze, effectively ruining them.

